Another important factor shaping a diverse array of plant traits, including morphological features, is climate (
 Nakazato, Bogonovich & Moyle, 2008; 
 Colautti & Barrett, 2013; 
 Van Boheemen, Atwater & Hodgins, 2019). Temperature and precipitation gradients are the main climatic factors driving the adaptive diversification of species (
 Nakazato, Bogonovich & Moyle, 2008). As it seems, climatic conditions have had a limited effect on the investigated seed parameters till now, due to a small area of secondary distribution of 
 I. capensis in Poland (
 Adamowski, My≈õliwy & Dajdok, 2018; 
 Fig. 1) and short time of residence of little over 30 years. Although this investigated plant has only a few localities inhabiting only a relatively small area in Poland, rapid expansion across environmental gradients has been reported for several plants introduced to a new area and species can evolve quite quickly driven by environmental factors (
 Dlugosh & Parker, 2008; 
 Colautti & Barrett, 2013; 
 Molina-Montenegro et al., 2018; 
 Van Boheemen, Atwater & Hodgins, 2019).
